Bob Dylan
BALL
HOLLYS
LAGNING

Bob Dylan
Believe it or not, Bob Dylan had no intention of becoming ahead for
American unrest in the early 1960's. He just wanted to make music and
chronicle the world he saw around him. And as a supremely talented singer,
songwriter, author, musician, and poet, he did a pretty darn good job at both.
Consequently, he ended up writing a number of songs that would become
anthems for the anti-war and civil rights movements.
Dylan began his life as Robert Zimmerman, but with a name change and an
untrained singing voice with a now famous edge to it, his career in the "new folk"
movement took off. His early lyrics combined politics with social commentary,
philosophy with obscure literary references and created a style that defied
convention. But Dylan's unique approach didn't end there. No. His musical prowess
extended into folk, country, blues, gospel, rock and roll, and even jazz.
All this combined just may be why one of his most famous songs is occasionally
misunderstood. You see, Dylan never meant for "The Times They Are a-Changin
to be an indictment on the generation gap or on political divide. It was part of album
of songs about racism, poverty and social change. An album that would go Gold and
